                        <interp inst="t18371023-name-1344" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18371023-2405-offence-1 t18371023-name-1344"></join>Henry Gray</persName>, his master.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18371023-name-1345" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18371023-name-1345" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18371023-name-1345" type="surname" value="GRAY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18371023-name-1345" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY GRAY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a farmer, and live at Barking. On Tuesday, the 17th of October, I and my wife were in town, and when I went home my daughter informed me that the prisoner had taken some wheat out of the barn—that is all I know about it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18371023-name-1346" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18371023-name-1346" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18371023-name-1346" type="surname" value="GRAY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18371023-name-1346" type="given" value="HARRIETT"></interp>HARRIETT GRAY</persName>
                  </hi>. A little after six o'clock on Tuesday evening I saw the prisoner hang his bag on the pales—he went in doors to take the key</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183710230201"></xptr>
               <p>of the barn in, and while he was gone I felt his bag and found some wheat in it—when he came out he took the bag off the pales—I asked what he had—he said he had not any thing but a basin—I said, "You have some<lb></lb>thing else"—he said he had—I said, "Let me see?"—I opened it and found the wheat—he said, "Let me take it back?"—I said, "No, you had better leave it for my father to see," and he left it—he had had the key of the barn, and there was wheat there.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18371023-name-1347" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18371023-name-1347" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18371023-name-1347" type="surname" value="GRAY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18371023-name-1347" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN GRAY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a constable. I took the prisoner, and have the property.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18371023-name-1348" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18371023-name-1348" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18371023-name-1348" type="surname" value="BIGGS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18371023-name-1348" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE BIGGS</persName>
                  </hi>, I am a farmer. On Tuesday evening, about seven o'clock, I had business at Mr. Gray's, and Miss Gray stated about the wheat being stolen—I went up the road and met the prisoner with some wheat on his back in a sack—I stopped him and took it from him—he said it was what his wife had been gleaning—I gave him into custody—the wheat which he had was not owned by any one.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18371023-name-1349" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18371023-name-1349" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18371023-name-1349" type="surname" value="GRAY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18371023-name-1349" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY GRAY</persName>
                  </hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> I have compared the wheat left with my daughter with what was in my barn—the prisoner said he took it, he could not tell why, he thought it must be the devil, who had very nearly got the upper hand of him the day before, but he beat him then—this was only the second day he had worked for me.</p>
               <p>
